-- FACTBOX: Koenigsegg and Saab: an unlikely car duo
-- 
-- Wed Jun 17, 2009 5:41am EDT
-- http://www.reuters.com/article/2009/06/17/us-gm-saab-koenigsegg-factbox-sb-idUSTRE55F2QC20090617

 

 (Reuters) - Swedish sportscar maker Koenigsegg and General Motors GMGMQ.PK have struck a preliminary deal for the niche firm to take over loss-making carmaker Saab Automobile after two decades of U.S. ownership, it was announced on Tuesday. 

 Below are some facts about Koenigsegg and Saab Automobile: COMPANY HISTORIES * Koenigsegg, founded by Christian von Koenigsegg in 1994, makes high-performance sportscars. The company's headquarters is in Angelholm, in southern Sweden, using an aircraft hangar that once housed Swedish airforce Gripen fighter jets made by defense group Saab AB. * Saab Automobile has made cars in Trollhattan, southwest Sweden since 1949. GM bought 50 percent of the firm in 1989 when Saab Automobile was established as an independent company. GM bought the rest of Saab Automobile in January 2000. * Koenigsegg is part-owned by Norwegian entrepreneur Bard Eker through his holding company Eker Group AS, which owns a 49 percent stake in Koenigsegg. PRODUCTION * Saab sold 93,295 vehicles globally in 2008, representing 1.1 percent of total GM sales volume, down 25 percent from 2007. * Saab's 9-5 and 9-3 models are built in Trollhattan. The 9-3 Cabriolet is made by Magna Steyr in Graz, Austria. GM plans to move production of Saab 9-5 to its Opel factory in Ruesselsheim, Germany, in 2009. There are also plans for new 9-5 and 9-3 models and a 9-4 sports utility vehicle. * Koenigsegg manufactures only a handful of its exclusive cars per year. Last year it made 18 cars. * Koenigsegg makes the CCX, one of the world's fastest and most powerful production cars, capable of speeds of more than 395 kilometers (245 miles) an hour. STAFF * Saab employs around 3,400 by May 18, 2009 * Koenigsegg has a staff of 45. FINANCIALS * Saab, which has not made a profit since 2001, has estimated its 2008 loss at 3 billion Swedish crowns ($384 million) and said it expected a similar result for 2009. The company hopes to reach profitability around 2011. * Koenigsegg reported sales of 106 million crowns ($13.8 million) last year. (Sources: Saab Automobile, GM Sweden, GM Europe, Swedish Companies Registration Office, Koenigsegg website and spokeswoman) ($1=7.669 Swedish Crown) (Compiled by Stockholm Newsroom; Editing by Greg Mahlich)